column168: Clean Harbors personnel were weighing a fiberboard Co-pack on a scale when a small amount of liquid was observed leaking from the bottom corner of the box.  As the box was being removed from the scale the Co-pack tipped over causing the top flaps to open and additional small amount of liquid emptied onto the floor.  The Co-pack was then lifted up.  Response personnel cleaned up spillage donning the proper PPE.  The inner liner was removed from the Co-pack, and placed into a second liner. Both liners were then repack into another Co-pack container. The Co-pack container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: Recommeded to the generator that all solid containers that contain liquids, be closed tightly before placing them into the fiberboard container that has an inner liner inserted.  Also recommended using two inner liners.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: 01/06/14:  At approximately 05:50AM, CR Car Inspector noted product cascading down side(s) of tank car UTLX 206782, load Alcohols, NOS, while car was on track #8 Receiving.      Unseasonably warm weather (54 degrees F.), with heavy intermintent rain.  Further inspection by CR A. Richter, Risk Management, CR S. Hart, Mechanical Department Supervisor, and 2 representatives of environmental/hazmat emergency response contractor Hepaco-React, found the 3" liquid ball valve, located under the protective housing cover, partially opened.  Valve was closed, securing release.  2" air valve was partially opened during the inspection to vent car down.  Once completed, the liquid valve was re-opened, allowing contained product remaining above the closed ball, to empty back into the car.    Both the air and liquid valves had "quick connect" closure caps.  However, the liquid valve closure cap did not secure properly, as when the locking ears were secured in place as designed, the cap could be spun.     Original Shipper seal "Lincolnland A-E 0026327" was intact and removed from the protective housing for inspection of interior valves/leak source.  Seal was replaced with Hepaco-React cable seal (number not recorded).     Car was released for delivery to original consignee.  Consignee has been notified about the liquid valve closure cap and will contact UTLX Mobile Repair to inspect/repair/replace defective cap.

column168: On January 5, 2013, at approximately 1715 hours personnel in the CSXT Erwin Yard discovered UTLX 667718, a loaded tank car of Xylenes leaking from the top.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Chevron Phillips Chemical Company, was notified CHEMTREC Report 2017-01-05-00053.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a product leak at the connection between the threaded valve and the tank car on the liquid line due to the valve being less than tool tight.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative, Daniel Lopez 281-900-6677.  Contractor personnel removed the liquid valve, inspected and cleaned the valve and liquid line threads, applied thread sealant, and re-installed the liquid line valve.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transport under a OTMA to allow offloading, and subsequent re-qualification of the liquid line valve.  NAR Cause Code: 282  NARRI:  5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60

column168: Employee noted bad smell coming from tank car PROX 60520.  Car was isolated and a contractor was called to investigate.  Contractor found the caps on the liquid and vapor lines were not secured.  They were tightened and solidified sulfur on the top of the car was washed off.  The car was allowed to sit for a while and was metered again for SO2.  Hits of 150ppm were found to be coming from the manway area.  Contractor opened the manway and found the gasket to be deteriorated.  Gasket was replaced and manway properly torqued.  Car was released back into transportation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: During a routine yard check of the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility, a rolloff box was found be be leaking a small amount of liquid from the rear tailgate.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spilled material with an aborbent material, placing it all back into the box.  The rear door was tightened and the leak stopped.
column169: The shipper was notified of the incident and advised to review their solidification procedures to insure against liquids separating from the solid material during transportation.

column168: Clean Harbors was off loading four steel drums shrink wrap to a wooden pallet that was not a standard size of Dichloroaniline from a van trailer. As the pallet was placed on the warehouse floor one of the drums fell off the pallet damaging the top causing approximately 35 gallons to be released. A Clean Harbors response team donned the proper PPE and placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris from the warehouse. The container was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: Informed the generator that drums should be properly secured to a pallet by something other than shrink wrap, and that the pallets need to be large enough that all four drums can be secured properly.  Plant personell to evaluate load stability moving forward prior to offloading.

column168: An apparent 275 gallon tote had an unsecured lid that popped off in transit releasing an estimated 2 gallons of product to the trailer floor and adjacent cargo. The release was was estimated to be ~ 1 hour and a contractor was dispatched to the site to secure the tote and cleanup the released material. column168: A tanker trailer was being loaded with hazardous waste from a railcar at the customer's location.  The customer's operator asked the driver if he could tell how full the tanker was getting.  The driver responded affirmatively but had to get back into the cab to watch his suspension gauge.  When it started getting full he got out but the operator had left the area.  The driver was not allowed to operate the customer's equipment and went to find the operator.  When the operator was located and returned he closed the railcar valve but the tanker trailer was overfilled and leaking from the pump exhaust.  An in house response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spilled material.  The driver pumped the spilled material back into the railcar.  The spilled material was cleaned from the side of the tanker and the loading was completed without further incident.
column169: The customer's operator was to be retrained in the importance of not leaving the area when actively loading tankers.  The driver was advised to insure all parties are clear as to their role in staying with equipment that is being loaded and unloaded.

column168: Apparently on Monday 1/14/13 a 275 gallon tote of the material was punctured by a fork on a forklift at the terminal. Terminal employees secured the release and conducted initial cleanup. A contractor was dispatched to the site on Wednesday to transfer the tote into a new tote. It was identified that the material had impacted a dumpster, the pavement around the dumpster and a nearby drain. On Thursday 1/16/13, the contractor was dispatched to clean the dumpster, the impacted pavement and clean out the drain system. All waste was containerized and staged on site for pending disposal.

column168: On January 16, 2014, apparently a mechanic was installing a placard to the trailer wall. While drilling through the wall, the drill drilled a whole in the side of a 330 gallon tote releasing an estimated 15 gallons to the trailer floor. On site personnel secured the release with absorbents. The contractor arrived on site and transferred the damaged tote into drums and staged them on site to be returned to the shipper for reclamation. The contractor then cleaned up the impacted trailer floor and all waste was  left on site until disposal could be coordinated.

There was no package failure.  The consignee ordered more product than their underground storage tank could hold. column168: The CTMV driver arrived at the consignee, connected the hoses, and opened the dome cover in preparation to unload.  He then realized he should be unloading to a different storage tank in a different part of the plant, so he disconnected the hoses, and closed the dome cover.  Apparently the dome cover was not adequately secured, and while he was moving the CTMV to the other part of the plant, product sloshed out of the CTMV's dome opening to the plant's driveway, parking area and adjacent soils approximately 10' by 20'.  The release duration was limited to when the CTMV was being moved.  A hazardous materials response contractor was dispatched to the plant to decontaminate the CTMV and the affected areas.

column168: NS Mechanical employee reported tank car TAEX 1013 leaking on Track 901 in the yard.  Car was isolated and a contractor called.  Contractor inspected car and found Top Operated Bottom Outlet Valve (TOBOV) not closed completely.  They were able to get 3/4 of a turn on the TOBOV stem.  The bottom outlet cap was also loose and the contracor was able to get over one complete turn on the cap with a wrench.
column169: No additional comments.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: HV32 yard crew reported they smelled an odor of LPG while switching tank car GATX 9087.  Yardmaster had the crew clear the area and the car was isolated.  NS Environmental was notified and a contracctor called to inspect the car.  Contractor open the protective housing cover and found the "A" end liquid line valve open and the plug loose.  The valve was partially iced over.  Contractor closed the valve, removed, cleaned, taped, and reapplied the plug wrench tight.  Protective housing area was then metered for flammable gas readings and none were found.  Car was released back into transporation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: This release was not caused by a package failure.  Our driver was loading the CTMV, and did not verify that the inlet valves for both compartments of the multi-compartment CTMV were open.  Once the first compartment was full, product released from the CTMV vent, as designed.  Upon observation of the release, our driver turned off the transfer pump, ending the release. The driver than continued loading after opening the other valve and finished loading both compartments. The released product impacted a frozen and snow-covered area of about 25' x 35'.  A hazardous materials response contractor was dispatched to the well site to decontaminate the affected areas.     QCER E39679

column168: Tanker 70006T was being prepped to load a Xylene solution.  Prior to loading, the  customer purged the tanker with Nitrogen.  During this process a small leak was discovered at the rear manway.  The wing nuts of manway were tighten and the Nitrogen leak stopped. There were no others areas that leaked during the purging operation.  The customer then started transferring the Xylene solution into the tanker and after about 4 minutes there was a small release of Xylene solution released from a flange that is connected to bottom piping of the tanker. A drip pan was immediately placed under the flange and the transfer was stopped. The flange was tighten and the transfer resume without futher incident and the material was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility..

column168: IN THE UPS JACKSONVILLE, FL HUB AT APPROXIMATELY 22:00 HRS ON 1/5/2014, A PADDED ENVELOPE SHIPPED VIA UPS GROUND SERVICE WAS TRAPPED IN SORTING EQUIPMENT AND BEGAN TO SMOLDER. IT WAS REMOVED FROM THE CONVEYOR BELT AND PLACED ON THE CONCRETE FLOOR, WHERE THE SMOLDERING STOPPED OF ITS OWN ACCORD. INVESTIGATION SHOWED THE CONTENTS TO BE A REPLACEMENT LITHIUM ION BATTERY PACK FOR A LAPTOP COMPUTER.  THE BATTERY, INSERTED INTO A PLASTIC BAG, WAS PACKED IN A SMALL FIBERBOARD BOX THAT DISPLAYED THE LITHIUM ION BATTERY HANDLING LABEL. THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS IN TURN PLACED INTO THE PADDED ENVELOPED FOR SHIPMENT. AS A RESULT OF THE HEAT RELEASED IN THE INCIDENT, THE BATTERY PACK WAS MELTED AND SOME PACKAGING MATERIAL WAS CHARRED.  THERE IS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE PACKAGING WAS INADEQUATE. UPS SUSPECTS THAT THE TRAPPING OF THE PACKAGE IN MATERIAL HANDLING EQUIPMENT APPLIED SUFFICIENT STRESS TO THE BATTERY TO CAUSE IT TO RELEASE SIGNIFICANT HEAT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR OTHER DAMAGES RESULTING FROM THIS INCIDENT.

column168: During a routine inspection, it was discovered that approximately two gallons of an unknown material leaked from a van trailer that was parked at Clean Harbor’s in transit storage location in Tucker, GA for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation to the intended waste management facility. Clean Harbors personnel donning personal protective equipment entered the van trailer located a close top 55 gallon metal container in good condition which had a small leak at the bottom of the container.  The leaking container was placed into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris from inside and outside the van trailer. The container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: Reminded all drivers that prior to loading containers into van trailers and box trucks that the flooring be inspected for objects such as nails, stones, etc that could possibly breach a container during transit.

column168: There was no packaging failure.  The Consignee's above ground storage tank overflowed while the CTMV was unloading.  The release impacted a 60' x 60' soil containment area. The release stopped when the transfer pump was turned off. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site to remediate the impacted soil.    QCER E39691.

On Jan.6th Veolia made routine drum pick up from UPS Jacksonville, FL of 49 drums of hazardous & non-hazardous waste. Upon completion of manifests & associated paperwork and loading of the vehicle the driver departed for FCI in Bartow,Fl. where the truck would be off loaded.    Veolia arrived at FCI, Bartow, Fl. @ approx. 1300 and backed truck to the receiving dock and went inside with paperwork to complete 10 Day documentation and copying scanning manifest copies for 10 day in-transit documentation to the Veolia Morrow GA office.    At approx. 1345 the Veolia driver returned to receiving dock and opened the back door of vehicle to prepare for unloading. He immediately noticed a colored fume in the back of truck.  Upon further investigation, he observed that all the shipping labels attached to the packagings had turned to a light orange and there was a bulging drum labeled Oxidizer & Corrosive at the rear of truck. The Veolia driver immediately called his supervisor to report the incident. FCI secured their property by closing gates and sheltered all personnel on site in office building.    FCI contaced an off-site emergency response team to manage the drum.  FCI also notified the local Fire Department.  At approximately 1445 the local Fire Dept/HazMat crew arrived, monitored the scene and did not institute any evacuations.     The ER crew started remediating drum and contents. The response team discovered that there had been 5 x 2.5L glass bottles that were packed in one plastic bag with no surrounding absorbent and that one bottle had broken and breached plastic bag. The response team repackaged all the drum contents into 3 new containers.
column169: Ensure Proper Segregation of Nitric Acid by Veolia prior to packaging by UPS.    Review of packing slips by Veolia Field Technician/Operations Supervisor prior to accepting load at UPS.    Proper packaging and containment of leaking containers by UPS.    Use of proper absorbent material for packaging nitric acid (no organic materials ie Klexall)

column168: On January 20, 2014 at 23:15 hours personnel in the CSXT Radnor Yard detected an odor from CAOX 200101, a residue tank car of Chlorine. HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the A-end Liquid Line Valve closure plug less than tool tight, and the valve partially open.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative, Todd Tucker 903-987-3248.  The Liquid Line Valve was closed, Closure Plug secured, and the car released for transport.       NARRI: 5(4+10+1) x (2+0) = 150  Cause Code: 119

column168: A Landstar tractor trailer was transporting a shipment of 275 gallon totes and 2.5 gallon jugs of herbicide on January 16, 2014. A severe dust storm kicked up on Highway 34 which significantly reduced visibility. The tractor trailer following the Landstar trailer did no compensate his speed accordingly which caused that trailer to drive into the Landstar trailer. 2 totes of the herbicide were crushed due to the accident. 12 vehicles in total were involved in this accident. Emergency responders were first on site and applied absorbents to contain the release. Additional environmental contractors were dispatched to clean the spill. Belfor of Denver, CO responded to the spill to complete remediation activities. Belfor personnel applied absorbents to clean released material and cleaned the product from the damaged trailer. The soil section of the roadway that was impacted by the release is scheduled to be excavated to remove any residual product on site.

column168: Tank car UTLX 206453 was reported with commodity on its side shell while in the railyard. Inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder revealed the leak source was at the 165 psi pressure relief valve (PRV). The PRV valve stem moved freely which is indicative of a broken valve stem, broken spring or a failed spring retaining mechanism. UTLX 206453 was carefully isolated in the railyard awaiting a suitable PRV replacement and installation. Contract responders cleaned the spillage from UTLX 206453's side shell. A replacement PRV was installed (1/14/2014) and OTMA FRA-14010014 was granted to transport UTLX 206453 to the consignee for unloading, then to a certified repair facility.
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: Residue tank car ECLX 16131 in the railyard was reported with a slow commodity drip emanating from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) near the threaded bottom outlet cap (BOC) connection. BNSF responders were able to stop the dripping by tightening the threaded BOC connection. ECLX 16131 was isolated in the railyard for continued observation.  On 1/09/2014, ECLX 16131 was observed dripping residue commodity again and a containment receptacle placed under the BOV. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders closed the top operated bottom outlet valve's (TOBOV) operating rod 1/8 turn and retightened the BOC connection. The dripping ebbed to approximately one drop per minute. Contract responders were summoned to assist in ending the commodity drips and secure the BOV-BOC connection. The responders removed residual commodity from within ECLX 16131 which ended any further residue commodity drips. Afterwards, responders cycled the TOBOV and cleaned some debris from the bottom valve seat area. The inside of the BOC was cleaned and the BOC gasket replaced. New Teflon tape was applied to the threaded BOC connection and the BOC was tool tightened. Two disposal drums of removed commodity and contaminated materials were earmarked for appropriate disposal.   ECLX 16131's side stenciling indicated that its last tank qualification was accomplished in the year 2007.   ECLX 16131 was redirected to a qualified repair facility.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and the mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The railcar arrived into Truck-Rail Handling at Snoboy siding on Friday 1/11/2014 in the late evening. While performing the inbound railcar arrival inspection on Sunday 1/13/2014, it was discovered that this railcar was leaking on arrival. Upon inspection, it was found that it was dripping very slowly out of the unloading lower valve from the flange where the main valve or lower external valve bolts to the tank of the railcar. A catch pan was put under the leak. We collected product that leaked into pan and found it was about 1 oz. a day of leaked product. We contacted the Shipper (BASF) to notify them of the leaking railcar. We also contacted our local DOT "Railroad Safety Inspector Hazardous Materials" contact, Gary Flores. We also took pictures and brought them down to our local fire department in Fremont CA and provided them the MSDS, BOL for the railcar, and the pictures taken. Tom Hervey (State of California Association, Transportation Supervisor Hazardous Materials) was notified by our DOT contact. We also notified the State of California Governor's Office Emergency Services (OES) which in turn provided a control number(14-0252). After the (OES) notice went out to Government agencies, we received a call from Fremont Fire Department (Hazardous Materials Technician) Jacqueline Nomany. Jacqueline Nomany came out to verify the extend of the leak. The Shipper (BASF) scheduled the UTLX maintenance crew to come out and inspect the railcar and see if they can tighten the bolts of the leaking flange gasket and stop the leak. The UTLX maintenance crew was not able to fix the leak, so on Thursday 1/23/2014, the product was transferred out of the leaking railcar into a recently emptied railcar that contained the same product. We will now use the new railcar for future loads. The defective railcar will be shipped out by the Shipper (BASF) who is requesting an OTMA.

column168: TRUCK OPERATED BY CONTRACT CARRIER TRANSPORT AMERICA TRANSPORTING FEDEX EXPRESS FREIGHT WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON INTERSTATE 57 NEAR MILE MAKER 1 IN ILLINOIS ON ICY ROAD AND HIT THE LEFT SIDE OF THE BRIDGE. THE TRUCK WAS HANGING OVER THE EDGE OF THE BRIDGE AND BURST INTO FLAMES. IT WAS ENGULFED WHEN EMERGENCY CREWS ARRIVES. THE DRIVER WAS THROWN FROM THE TRUCK ABOUT 100 FEET AWAY ONTO A CREEK BED UNDER THE BRIDGE.    ON MONDAY AFTERNOON, JANUARY 7, 2014, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TWO ABOVE DESCRIBED RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL PACKAGES WERE ON BOARD. THE REMNANTS OF THE TRACTOR TRAILER HAD BEEN TOWED TO A WREAKER YARD. ON TUESDAY, JANUARY 7, 2014 FEDEX EXPRESS MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL MET REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE BUREAU OF RADIATION SAFETY, ILLINOIS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY. THE IR-192 TYPE B PACKAGE WAS RECOVERED INTACT AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER, INDUSTRIAL NUCLEAR. THE PERKIN ELMER P-32 TYPE A HAD BEEN TOTALLY CONSUMED IN THE FIRE AND THERE WAS RESULTING CONTAMINATION IN THE VICINITY OF THE PACKAGE IN THE REMNANTS OF THE TRAILER NEAR THE FRONT. THE CONTAMINATION WAS SECURED TO PREVENT ANY RELEASE OR SPREAD. THE BUREAU OF RADIATION SAFETY, ILLINOIS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY HAS APPROVED DECAY IN STORAGE AND AFTER THE SPECIFIED DATE THE TRAILER AND IT CONTENTS WILL BE DISPOSED OF.

column168: On 1/2/14 at approximately 2345 company transport driver was traveling east bout on highway 51, 4 miles west of I35 near Stillwater, OK. While traveling in the left lane, for an unknown reason the driver failed to maintain his lane and departed the roadway left striking a guard rail and subsequent bridge barrier. After crossing the bridge, the transport truck departed the roadway completely and entered the center median causing the transport to roll-over and separated the tractor from the trailer. The tractor rolled over one complete time, and the trailer rolled over and come to reset lying on its side. As a result of the crash the driver sustained multiple blunt force injuries and approximately 300 gallons of diesel fuel was released from the manway hatch of the front compartment on the cargo tank. The spill area impacted an approximate area of 20x30 yards. No waterway was impacted. Duration of release was approximately five hours at an unknown rate of loss. Environmental response team was immediately dispatched to respond to the spilled diesel fuel. The cleanup crew used traditional remedial process to contain and recover lost diesel fuel by excavation and removal of the contaminated soil. The site has been restored to pre-accident condition.
column169: The root cause (reason why the driver left roadway) is still under investigation. Therefor recommendations for improvement is still pending.

column25: United States Post Office on Behalf of Provision Interanational Inc
column168: Dispatch number 0119, shipped under United States Post Office tracking number 9405 5102 0098 6183 5034 83/ 1pc weighing 5kgs, consisted of a parcel containing six 12 oz. aerosol cans containing Dust-Off, Electronics Duster (UN1030 / total net qty. 2.129 L).    The mail shipment originated in New York (JFKIA) and was accepted by Emirates from the United States Post Office as a mail consignment, under  document number AV-7: US14MOR04024. The parcel was then transported on flight EK206 on January 22nd, 2014 from JFK International Airport to Dubai  International Airport. The shipment was packaged in a way that prevented Emirates’ handling staff from verifying its contents without opening the  parcel. Contents were discovered during a routine x-ray screening of transit mail by the Dubai Police. After Dubai Police opened the package, it was  discovered that the internal containers contained the Dust-off Dusters in original packaging. Hazmat documentation was not provided to Emirates by the  shipper at the time of tender. After classifying shipment as suspect D.G., Emirates contacted the shipper for confirmation of the contents. At which  point the shipper confirmed that the aerosol cans had been shipped in the US Mail in error. The shipment is currently being held in Dubai, until shipper  appoints an agent to perform proper markings, labeling, and documentation. Only after all IATA/ICAO and FAA requirements have been met, the  shipment will be moved to its final destination Djibouti, or returned back to the shipper.
column169: Shipper appears to be a wholesaler operating under Amazon.com.  This type of shipper needs to traing their staff in Dangerous Goods Handling By air in accordance to the ICAO regulation, as they are shipping internatinaly.

Clean Harbors driver was loading a Vacuum Box onto a roll-off trailer frame when a liquid material began leaking from the back door area.  The Vacuum Box was immediately lowered back to the ground which caused the leak to stop.  The driver attempted to pick up a second Vacuum Box that was on site and a small amount of material leaked from that box and the driver immediately lowered that box back to the ground causing leak to stop. Clean Harbors personnel responded donned appropriate Personal Protective Equipment(PPE),cleaned up the material on the ground and placed the contaminated soil into another Vacuum Box.  The waste material from both both Vacuum Boxes were transfered to other Vacuum Boxes and contuinued in transportation to intended disposal facility without incident. It was determined that gasket material that sealed the back door may have became rigid and failed, due to extreme cold temperatures causing the liquid material to leak out the back door when the Vacuum Box was elevated.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has  been re-instructed to insure that a comprehensive inspection of a container's body along with the closure device to identify any potential issues before  transportation.  Recommendations were also made to not allow sludge material to sit inside a Vacuum Box for a long period of time during extreme cold temperatures which could cause the gaskets to become rigid and not seat tightly against the container.

column168: At approximately 0545 EST on 01/09/14, a R&L Carriers tractor trailer rolled over while exiting I-75 at exit ramp 265.    ERTS was notified of the rollover at 0711 EST.  ERTS contacted Hull's Environmental, and dispatched them to the scene.    Hull's personnel arrived at the site at approximately 0830 EST, but were unable to access the rolled-over trailer until approximately 1000 EST, due to the local fire department not allowing access to the site.  At 1043 EST, Hull's personnel reported to ERTS that one drum of UN1993 Heptane/isopropanol had been damaged during the rollover, and released approximately 20 gallons of material to the interior of the trailer.    Upon discovery of the leaking drum, Hull's personnel overpacked the drum, securing the release and then applied absorbents to the released material.

ON THURSDAY, JANUARY 16TH, 2014 THERE WAS A DIESEL FUEL SPILL AT LELAND OLDS STATION IN STANTON, ND. WHEN OUR DRIVER ARRIVED ON SITE THE UNLOADING PIPE WAS LOCKED. HE THEN PROCEEDED TO FIND A LOS EMPLOYEE WHO UNLOCKED THE TANKS FOR HIM. THE LOS EMPLOYEE READ THE DIGITAL TANK MONITOR AND TOLD OUR DRIVER TO UNLOAD. AFTER PERIOD OF TIME THE LOS EMPLOYEE CAME BACK AND TOLD THE DRIVER TO SHUT OFF HIS PUMP AS THE DIESEL WAS COMING OUT THE TOP OF THE TANK. FROM WHERE OUR TRUCKS UNLOAD THE TANKS ARE NOT VISIBLE DUE TO THE LARGE CONTAINMENT WALL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE 6 FOOT TALL CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA AND GATE VALVE WAS LOCKED SHUT.    THE CLEAN UP WAS DONE BY LOS EMPLOYEES. THEY WERE ABLE TO PUMP THE SPILLED FUEL AND DISCARDED IT INTO THE OIL BURNER.

On January 14, 2014, a Landstar tractor trailer hauling 20 totes of UN1903 Corrosive Liquid left the roadway, and rolled down a small embankment into the soil median. Three of the totes were compromised after being crushed during the accident. It is estimated that 400 gallons of material had released to an estimated 15'x100'in area. After the release occurred, Landstar called ERTS to manage the environmental response, and ERTS dispatched Freeman Environmental of Herrin, IL to the site. Freeman Environmental neutralized the area, and secured it with absorbent boom and poly sheeting for pending excavation.

column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: On January 17, 2014, at approximately 0100 EST, R&L Carriers personnel discovered that a 55 gallon drum of UN1805 Phosphoric Acid had been punctured by a forklift, releasing its entire contents to the interior of the trailer, and on to the ground below the trailer.    R&L Carriers contacted ERTS at approximately 0111 EST.  ERTS contacted HazChem, an environmental contractor, to respond to the incident.      HazChem personnel responded to the site.  They applied oil dry and bicarbonate to the interior areas of the trailer affected by the released material.  The punctured drum was overpacked.  Freight which had been impacted by the released material was removed from the trailer and wiped down. Oil dry and debris was containerized in to drums for disposal.

THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EAST ON I-69. THE ROAD WAS ICY. THE VEHICLE SKIDDED ON THE ICE. THE VEHICLE CONTACTED A GUARDRAIL (THAT WAS ALREADY BENT) ON THE SOUTH SHOULDER. THE VEHICLE CONTINUED CONTACTING THE CEMENT BRIDGE ABUTMENT AND CONTINUED RIDING THE CEMENT UNTIL THE VEHICLE TRAVELED OFF THE BRIDGE AND ONTO THE NORTHBOUND LANES OF IRISH ROAD. AFTER MAKING CONTACT WITH THE ROAD BELOW, THE TANKER CAUGHT ON FIRE. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO MAKE IT OUT BEFORE THE FIRE STARTED. THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE BOB BISSELL TRUCKING OFFICE. BOB BISSELL IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED GREAT LAKES PETROLEUM TRANSPORTATION. DAVISON FIRE CHIEF TOOK CHARGE OF THE SEEN AND MADE ALL OF THE APPROPRIATE EMERGENCY PHONE CALLS AND TOLD BOB BISSELL NOT TO MAKE ANY EMERGENCY PHONE CALLS BECAUSE THEY WOULD BE DUPLICATE CALLS.
column169: BOB BISSELL TRUCKING HAS ALWAYS BELIEVED IN THE IMPORTANCE OF DRIVER TRAINING. HOWEVER, IN LIEU OF THIS INCIDENT, WE ARE STEPPING UP OUR CURRENT TRAINING METHODS. NOT ONLY ARE WE KEEPING UP WITH OUR REGULAR TRAINING, BUT WE ARE NOW ADDING AN EMPHASIS ON TANKER ROLLOVER PREVENTION. ALL OF OUR DRIVERS ARE REQUIRED TO WATCH KEEP THE LOAD ON THE ROAD - A DRIVER'S GUIDE TO CARGO TANK TRUCK ROLLOVER PREVENTION AT WWW.FMCSA.DOT.GOV/ROLLOVERPREVENTION.  ANOTHER AREA WE ARE PAYING CLOSE ATTENTION TO IS THE WEATHER. SO FAR, THE WEATHER CONDITONS IN MICHIGAN HAVE BEEN EXCEPTIONALLY BAD THIS WINTER. WE ARE MAKING SURE EACH OF OUR DRIVERS KNOW TO TAKE THEIR TIME AND NOT TO DRIVE TOO FAST FOR THE WEATHER CONDITIONS. WE ARE PROMOTING SAFETY ABOVE ARRIVAL TIMES. OUR TRUCKS WILL BE PARKED IF THE WEATHER CONDITIONS ARE EXTREME AND WILL NOT BE ALLOWED TO RESUME DRIVING UNTIL THE CONDITIONS ARE IMPROVED AND I (BOB BISSELL) HAVE AUTHORIZED THE DRIVER TO BEGIN.

column168: A vacuum box container trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shipper’s location to be returned to the initial shipper. During the course of the trip, the driver conducted a routine load check and discovered a small amount of material coming from the rear door seal of the vacuum box container leaking onto the trailer fender. The driver immediately placed a containment pail under the rear door and contacted his home dispatcher to request a response crew. Upon notification, a response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, removed the released material and placed it back into the vacuum box, tightened the rear door which stopped the leak: a containment diaper was secured to the vacuum box as an added measure. the shipment was them re-routed to Clean Harbors' Kimball, NE facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. Upon inspection at the Clean Harbors' Kimball, NE facility it was determined the vacuum box was leaking due to the presence of free liquid. In order to prevent a recurrence, the initial shipper has been notified of the improper preparation and presence of free liquids in a solid waste stream, the driver has been re-instructed to perform a comprehensive inspection of the container's body along with the closure device to identify any potential issues before transportation. In addition, this specific container was placed out of service pending an inspection of the door seal.

column169: It was unusual for a container to leak-these are normally sturdy and designed for the product it holds. column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: On 1/08/2014, entrained tank car UTLX 207218 activated a main track Trackside Acoustic Detector System (TADS) alarm for a warm wheel roller bearing warning. UTLX 207218 was set-out from its train at a nearby industrial track. On 1/13/2014, a BNSF track inspector observed and reported a commodity stain that emanated from the top fitting area of UTLX 207218 while it remained motionless at its current location. Afterwards, inspection by BNSF mechanical responders revealed that UTLX 207218's liquid valve was not fully closed and this valve's closure plug was not in a tool tight condition. The responders closed the liquid valve and tool tightened its closure plug which ended any further commodity release at the closure plug's orifice. Responders wiped spillage from around the liquid valve, atop the valve housing plate and the top side shell of UTLX 207218. On 1/20/2014, contract responders re-inspected UTLX 207218's securement with no exceptions noted. Ground spillage was remediated via excavation of impacted frozen snow followed by an application of Micro-Blaze.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: AXIALL CORPORATION RESPONSE AFTER BEING NOTIFIED BY WATCO OF CAR CONDITION:  AXIALL ARRIVED AT WATCO RAIL SITE ON WEDNESDAY 1/22/2014 AND RECEIVED PERMISSION TO GO TO AND WORK ON THE RAIL CAR. UPON ARRIVING AT THE CAR, AXIALL FOUND A SMALL LINE OF CAUSTIC DOWN ONE SIDE AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF TOP OF CAR ALSO. LEE HUDON FROM THE FRA HAD MARKED THE DOME OF CAR WHERE THE LOOSE BOLTS WERE LOCATED. AXIALL FOUND TWO OF THE EYEBOLTS TO BE HAND TIGHT. THE MANWAY LID WAS OPENED AND THE GASKET WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION. AXIALL NEUTRALIZED THE CAUSTIC AND CLEANED THE CONTAMINATED AREAS. AXIALL THEN CLOSED THE CAR AND REPLACED ALL SEALS WITH NEW ONES. NEW SEAL NUMBERS ARE: DOME 3258407, INTERNAL 005069 AND VALVE BOX 005062. KEITH KIRBY OF GATX MOBILE CREW ARRIVED AND INSPECTED THE CAR WITH NO FINDINGS. AXIALL RETURNED TO THE WATCO RAIL OFFICE; CHECKED OUT AND LET WATCO KNOW THE REPAIR AND CLEANUP WAS COMPLETE WAS COMPLETE AND CAR WAS READY TO CONTINUE TO FINAL DISTINATION.
column169: INCIDENT WAS REVIEWED WITH FRA INSPECTOR LEE HUDON ON 2/3/2014. THE FOLLOWING ACTIONS WILL BE TAKEN BY AXIALL:    AXIALL LONGVIEW DOCUMENTS CA-OP-05(CAUSTIC RAILCAR LOADING) AND CA-CK-02(CAUSTIC RAILCAR LOADING/UNLOADING CHECKLIST) WILL BE SENT OUT FOR RE-TRAINING TO ALL QUALIFIED LOADING PERSONNEL THROUGH THE ELECTRONIC DOCUMENT MANAGEMENT SYSTEM.    THE EVEN WILL BE ADDED TO THE AXIALL LONGVIEW MONTHLY SAFETY MEETING SLIDES TO REVIEW THE INCIDENT WITH ALL LONGVIEW PLANT PERSONNEL.    AXIALL LONGVIEW WILL INVESTIGATE OTHER METHODS OF SECURING MANWAY EYEBOLTS INCLUDING METHODS USED AT OTHER AXIALL SITES TO ENSURE CONSISTENCY.

Tank car GATX 53294 was reported in the railyard emanating a commodity odor. Immediate inspection by BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders revealed that the applied manway gasket appeared compressed and not sealing properly (leaking commodity vapors). The responders installed a new manway gasket and properly resecured the manway closure. Afterwards, the odor/vapor dissipated and was no longer detectable. No liquid release was evident. Intact shipper seal numbered 003473 at the manway closure was replaced by seal BNSF 06157245.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: UTLX 900817, was discovered releasing crude oil from the top of the tank car. The cause of the release was a loose manway coverplate. The manway swing bolts were tightened.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: At approximately 1230 MT on 1/23/14 a Safety Kleen Systems Inc. power unit and semi trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous and non-hazardous waste was travelling southbound on Colorado state highway 71. At approximate mile marker 211.4 the vehicle’s right front steer tire left the roadway and entered the soft shoulder causing the power unit and semi trailer to lose control and travel down an inclined ditch and overturn onto the vehicle’s right side.  The loss of control and subsequent rollover collision caused the semi trailer’s contents to become unsecured. A total of two drums were ejected from the trailer and multiple additional containers within the semi trailer experienced a physical breach causing the release of their contents. An emergenciy response team was summoned, donned the proper personal protective equipment, and remediated the release. Several non regulated containers and one cubic yard container of regulated, packing group III material were remediated, repackaged, and sent to the original designated disposal facility.
column169: Counsel the driver on the importance of being attentive to and aware of road conditions at all times and operating the vehicle in the safest manner that conditions allow. A reduction in speed (estimated at 55-60 mph by Colorado State Patrol at the time of the accident) on curved, snow / ice covered roads is recommended. Disciplinary action per Clean Harbors' TC 2.1 Disciplinary Guidelines is pending.

column168: During the unloading phase of transportation, two 1-quart containers of UN3264 Phosphoric and Hydrochloric Acid were crushed on the dock. The containers released their entire contents to the concrete dock. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. Sodium Bicarbonate was used to neutralize the release and absorbents were deployed to contain the material. The absorbents were worked into the impacted area thoroughly and collected for disposal. The total area of impact was 2'x2'. No further impact remains at the release location.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: On 01/28/2014, at 20:14, personnel in the CSXT Tampa Terminal discovered NATX 300029, a loaded tank car of Alcohol NOS, leaking from the Bottom outlet Cap. The car was isolated and the shipper MGP Ingredients Inc., NRC and the Chemtrec were notified.  CHEMTREC Report # 2014-01-28-00232. SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the BOV cap cross threaded, gasket was worn.Valve was opened and closed several times and watched for further leaks with none occuring. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel corrected the gasket issue and resecured the BOV cap and cleaned up spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.    Cause Code: 149/5  NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A 55 gallon steel drum was noticed to be leaking a minimal amount of liquid from the bottom seam of the drum. It appears that there was no damage to the drum. Approximately 5 oz. of material was released from the drum due to what appears to be a faulty seam. The drum was placed on cardboard to absorb the release. When environmental contractors arrived on site the drum was flipped so the damaged section was moved to the vapor space and the drum was over-packed.

On January 30, 2014 at approximately 15:00 personnel on a main line train at CSXT MP BF 289 at the Bridge Street crossing in Smithton Pa. discovered PPRX 55132, a loaded tank car of Hexanes leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The train was held at that location and the shipper Phillips 66 Rob Yarbrough 281-627-3177, local, state and federal agencies as applicable were notified CHEMTREC Report # 2014-0130-00183. SPSI, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found bottom outlet valve cap loose. Cap was tightened and car moved to CSXT Connellsville yard. Cap continued to leak. Phillips 66 contacted a mobile repair company to replace cap and gasket. Phillips 66 obtained an OTMA-3 to move car onto destination once new cap was applied.    The leak was secured and OTMA applied for, the car was released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move.    NARRI=570   5X(5+3+0)X(2+0)=80
column169: No additional comments.

column168: After arrival on an inbound BNSF intermodal train, intermodal trailer GMLZ 221 was reported leaking an unknown viscous substance. GMLZ 221 was carefully taken to the facility's containment area for cargo inspection and spill remediation. Contract responders' investigating the leak source within GMLZ 221 reported finding four 55 gallon steel drums with minor cuts/punctures to their sidewalls. Three drums incurred small nicks/cuts under their top lids and the commodity seepage from these small cuts was drying on these drums sidewalls. Damage to these drums was suspected occurring during drum loading. One drum was found with an abrasion cut/puncture at its middle rolling hoop from rubbing against a metal cargo rack inside GMLZ 221. This drum's spillage seeped through the trailer flooring. All four damaged drums were placed into over-pack drums and returned to the lading after the spillage inside and outside of GMLZ 221 was cleaned. On site response was concluded by 1700 hrs. PST, 1/20/2014. One disposal drum of spent cleaning materials was earmarked for appropriate disposal.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: OUR TRACTOR-TRAILER LOADED WITH GASOLINE FOR DELIVERY AT A CONVENIENCE STORE. WHILE TRAVELING NORTH ON N.Y. STATE ROUTE 40 NEAR EASTON THE TRUCK DRIFTED OFF THE RIGHT SHOULDER. THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO BRING THE UNIT BACK ONTO THE HIGHWAY. THE TRUCK ROLLED INTO THE DITCH AND CAME TO REST UPSIDE DOWN. THERE WERE LARG ROCKS ON THE EMBANKMENT THAT PUT HOLES IN THE CARGO TANK AS IT SLID PAST THEM. THE TRACTOR CAB WAS CRUSHED AND OUR DRIVER WAS KILLED BY THE DESTRUCTION OF THE CAB, THE GASOLINE THAT SPILLED DID NOT PLAY A ROLE IN HIS DEATH. THE GASOLINE THAT SPILLED TRAVELLED DOWN THE DITCH AND THRU A CULVERT UNDER THE ROAD AND DOWN ONTO A WET FIELD AREA. FIRE & EMS RESPONDED AND USED FOAM TO SECURE THE AREA. THE WASHINGTON COUNTY SHERIFF'S OFFICE RESPONDED AND DOCUMENTED THE ACCIDENT. AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP COMPANY WAS BROUGHT IN AND THEY WERE ABLE TO DRILL THE TANK AND RECOVER 3500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. THE REMAINING 8000 GALLONS ENTERED THE DITCH AND FIELD. THE NYS DEPT OF ENVIRNOMENTAL CONSERVATION RESPONDED AND SUPERVISED THE CLEANUP EFFORTS, WHICH INCLUDED DITCHES AND HOLES TO COLLECT THE GASOLINE. HEAVY WRECKERS WERE BROUGHT IN TO SET THE TRACTOR-TRAILER BACK ONTO THE HIGHWAY FOLLOWING THE REMOVAL OF ANY REMAINING PRODUCT.  AT THAT TIME OUR DRIVER WAS REMOVED FROM THE CAB AND THE TRUCK WAS PUT ON FLATBEDS AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE. NO MEDICAL OR MECHANICAL REASON HAS BEEN DISCOVERED FOR THE TRUCK DRIFTING OFF THE HIGHWAY.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: We received a call from ABF freight systems in Pico Rivera, CA at 9:00 AM on Friday January 17, 2014 about a tank that was leaking. Juan Corona and Steve Williams responded to the call and went to the location to check out the tank. An ABF employee had reported smelling ammonia. ABF isolated this tank in an empty trailer in a remote part of their yard and blocked off access to the tank. We arrived and used litmus paper to identify the point of the leak, which was very small. We dispatch Airgas Specialty Products field service to the site where the tank was pumped out into a truck designed to pump out ammonia. When the tank was empty and everything was contained, the empty tank was transported back to the Airgas plant in La Mirada. The tank was filled to approximately 325 gallons of ammonia and the amount recovered in the pump out unit was also approximately 325 gallons.
column169: According to the personal who filled the tank, the tank was filled to 85% of fill capacity according to the float gauge on the tank. When field service arrived to pump out the tank, the float gauge was reading 90% which is higher than we fill these tanks. Also there was some corrosion on the relief valve that may have contributed to the leaking tank. We will perform better pre fill inspections on the tanks, replace any correded safety relief devices before filling tanks, and allow more time for the tanks to settle after filling and before shipping to make sure the amount on the gauge does not exceed 85%.

column168: CN transportation department employee reported an odor coming from tank car GATX 6228 (L / SULPHURIC ACID, SPENT UN1832) during normal switching operations at the CN Battle Creek Yard, Battle Creek, MI. column168: On January 22, 2014, a 55-gallon steel drum of UN1805 was punctured by a pallet due to a load shift resulting in the release of 1/2 gallon of product to the trailer floor. column168: An R&L Carriers tractor trailer was in an MVA and climbed up the center median, then caught fire. The accident caused drums of UN1263 to release flammable paint to the interior of the trailer and the pavement below. Due to the accident, the freight shifted forward in the load, crushing the drums in the nose of the trailer. Contractor used absorbents and boom to contain the released product and prevent impact to a storm drain. All cleanup debris was collected into drums and taken off site for profiling and disposal. The damaged drums were placed in over packs to prevent further release. No soils or waterways were impacted by the release.

Shipper's contractor responded finding man-way bolts less than tool tight and liquid/vapor valve plugs less than tool tight. Tank car secured contractor and released for movement to destination.

column168: It was reported that ~15 gallons of product was released in a trailer during loading from a 55-gallon drum. On January 21, 2014, a Dana Companies cargo tank motor vehicle experienced the release of 6 gallons of Fyrol PCF product due to product remaining in the hose at the time the driver disconnected it. The release impacted a 10' x 4' area of the wall and 4' x 8' area of the asphalt. An environmental contractor was dispatched to perform cleanup. The impacted areas were pressure washed utilizing a vacuum truck. All liquid was collected and containerized.

It was reported that a 55 gallon drum of UN1760 Corrosive Liquids was punctured due to a load shift. Approximately 1 gallon of material was released to the trailer floor. The material impacted the bottom of other drums in the load as well. Absorbents were used to contain the release on the floor, and pads were used to wipe down impact to other drums. All cleanup debris was placed into an over pack drum. No impact to the environment occurred as a result of this incident.

column168: The driver reported he was going the speed limit on a left hand curve.  He missed a pothole with this tractor but caught the tandems of the cargo tank causing the units to tip over.  Product started flowing out of the vacuum relief vent on the top of the cargo tank.  Approximately 1079 gallons spilled out before the first responder fire personnel were able to stop the leak. The remaining product was transferred to another cargo tank and the trailer was uprighted.  Road (state route)was closed for several hours.      Product spilled down an embankment and a small amount of product got into a tributary. An emergency response crew began working with the DEP to clean up the release and continue to monitor the soil samples.
column169: Drivers receive extensive training which includes rollover prevention.  It appears poor judgement may have played a role in this one.

column168: It was discovered that a 275-gallon tote of UN1993 released approximately 20 gallons of material to the trailer floor from a crack in the body of the tote. The total area of impact from the released product measured approximately 10'x6' inside the trailer. No impact to the environment occurred. Absorbents were used to contain the release. The release lasted no more than 3.5 hours.

It was discovered that a cargo tank motor vehicle was leaking NA1993 product due to what later was to be possibly caused by defective wipers on the indicator pins for the internal valve. Upon discovery a containment bucket was placed under the leak by the driver. The duration and rate of the release was estimated at .8 gallons per hour for approximately 3 hours. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site. Pumps and Hoses were set up to transfer material into a rescue tanker, as the valves were manipulated to begin transfer the internal valve on the malfunction tanker unit was stroked and the release sudden stopped. The unit was inspected to ensure that the valve was operating correctly which it was found to be. The captured material and any material in the hoses was put back into the unit and it continued onto the intended destination. Absorbents were applied to the impacted asphalt then containerized.

column168: At approximately 8:30 AM on January 20th, a Univar USA Inc. tractor-trailer was travelling east on the Pennsylvania Turnpike enroute to our facility in Morrisville PA.  The load had originated at our Middletown, PA facility.  In the area of mile marker 306, just west of the Morgantown exit, our driver was forced to brake very hard to avoid a vehicle that abruptly pulled off the road.  During this maneuver, the load shifted towards the front of the trailer.  A 330 gal Intermediate Bulk Container (IBC) filled with a 12.5% sodium hypochlorite solution, pushed forward into the wooden dunnage at the front of the trailer. The IBC was punctured by a board in the bottom third of the container, releasing an estimated 200-250 gallons of material into the roadway, shoulder and adjacent grassy area. There were no injuries.  The PA Turnpike Authority and Univar activated a spill response contractor (Lewis Environmental Inc.) to provide cleanup services.  The spilled hypochlorite was picked up by absorbents and the impacted soils excavated into a roadside stockpile.   An estimated 40 tons of vegetation and soils were excavated. The final site restoration is pending improvement in weather conditions.
column169: The Univar investigation has identified the following corrective measures:  -Purchase of additional securement load bars and straps,  -Refresher training for Univar operations employees.

column168: Description of Incident:   Mike arrived at his delivery location at Conserve FS 20048 N. Webster  Rd. Dekalb, IL. He was delivering #2 clear diesel and had never been  there before. He went inside and Julie that work there told him to put  it into tank # 1. As he started to pump the load off, he went out and  looked to make sure everything was going good and it was. When the first  compartment went empty ( 3000 gallons ) is when he noticed the large  spill ( 2010 gallons ). When he first read the tank he wrote down 3'.  The previous driver that had just left wrote down 26'-3" for his ending  reading. Mike read the tank wrong and thinking it would fit. The  location then sent him to another bulk plant to finish unloading because  it would not fit there. There was no overfill alarm on the tank, and no  containment for the tanks as they were double walled. The diesel ran off  the cement pad and onto a large ice cover area.    Update - I spoke to Julie at the site the day of incident - She state  the that driver did come in and talk to her. She informed him that tank  #1 and Tank #3 both were clear diesel tanks and that he would need to  get a reading prior to deliver. She also stated that the overfill  alarms were going off both flash light and sound. I also spoke with the  IL EPA contact that was on site yesterday and he tested the overfill  alarms and they were working appropriately.
column169: Action Taken:   Trans Environmental, 815-885-4840, came to clean up the spill. They had  a vac truck and a pickup and trailer full of supplies. They arrived at  11:45 AM and left at 2:00 PM All the puddled product was cleaned up.  Some snow / diesel was put into large totes. The tanks and surrounding  area would have to be cleaned up at a later date do to the weather.  There was some frozen soil involved which they said would have to be  scraped. David Myroth with Conserve FS (815-703-7915 ) is in charge of  the cleanup.    Root Cause:   Mike failed to read the guage properly and failed to notice the tank was  over filling.

column168: On 1-27-14, our tractor trailer picked up 17 IBC (totes) of a Corrosive liquid acid solution hydrochloric acid from Ohio Precious Metal located at 16064 Beaver Pike, in Jackson OH.  The IBCs were to be delivered to Alpha Omega Recycling Inc. located at 315 Whatley Rd in Longview, TX.  While in transport, our driver Mr. Raymond Lee, advised he was in heavy traffic on I-20 in a construction zone just prior to Little Rock, Arkansas when he had to brake harder then usual to avoid hitting a car. Mr. Lee stopped at a truck stop to get fuel for his truck when the leak was discovered.  Mr. Lee contacted his dispatcher and advised of the situation. At some point in the conversation with Mr.Lee and his dispatcher information was exchanged and the dispatcher believed that this was not a active leaking container. Mr. Lee was then told to drive to a clean-up contractors location approximately 15 miles away. Mr. Lee proceeded to Rineco to obtain assistance with the clean-up stopped along the side of Vulcan Road which is beside Rineco. A clean-up crew from Rineco arrived on location and began to attend to the leaking IBC.  It was determined that a IBC had shifted and a load lock handle puncture the IBC causing the leak.  Approximately 100 gallons of material had leaked and was recovered during the clean-up. After the clean occurred the tractor trailer delivered the remaining materials to Longview TX. There were no injuries or evacuations associated with the incident.

THE UPS FRIGHT DRIVER NOTICED "EMBERS" COMING FROM THE TRAILER VENT WHEN HE WAS CHECKING HIS MIRRORS AND IMMEDIATELY PULLED THE VEHICLE OVER AND REPORTED THE FIRE. WHEN FIRST RESPONDERS FROM THE LEXINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED, THEY BEGAN BY FLOWING WATER FROM THE TOP OF THE TRAILER INTO THE AFFECTED AREA. THEY ALSO CUT INTO THE SIDES OF THE TRAILER AND BROKE THE SEAL AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER FOR ACCESS. AFTER THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED, THE LEXINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENT ENTERED THE TRAILER, FINDING SEVERAL BOXES OF SCORCHED BEGGING, PILLOWS, AND OTHER ITEMS.  PICTURES TAKEN AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT INDICATE THAT SEVERAL ITEMS WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER DURING THE RESPONSE. THE LEXINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENT REPORT NOTES THAT THE TRAILER WAS NOT INVOLVED IN THE IGNITION, AND THAT THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE IS UNDETERMINED. HOWEVER, A REPORT FROM THE LEXINGTON POLICE DEPARTMENT DOES NOTE A SUSPECTED SOURCE OF IGNITION: "FIRE PATTERNS SUGGEST THAT THE FIRE ORIGINATED AT FLOOR LEVEL IN AN AREA WHERE MULTIPLE PALLETS OF USED NI-CD/RECHARGEABLE BATTERIES WERE PLACED FOR TRANSPORT. AFTER OBTAINING A COPY OF EACH BILL OF LADING, THE ONLY POSSIBLE IGNITION SEQUENCE COULD HAVE AND/OR WOULD HAVE BEEN FROM THE BATTERY AREA." THE LEXINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENT THEN RELEASED THE VEHICLE TO UPS FOR CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL, THE CONTENTS WERE RELOADED INTO THE TRAILER, AND THE TRAILER WAS TOWED BACK TO THE LEXINGTON UPS FREIGHT TERMINAL. THE FOLLOWING DAY, WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTORS, THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED AND SEVERAL PALLETS OF USED BATTERIES OF VARYING CHEMISTRIES WITH EXTENSIVE FIRE DAMAGE WERE FOUND IN THE AFFECTED AREA. THE CONSENSUS FROM THE RESPONDERS AND UPS MANAGEMENT ON SCENE WAS THAT THE FIRE HAD ORIGINATED FROM A PALLET CONTAINING LEAD-ACID BATTERIES, THOUGH THE SEQUENCE OF EVENTS WHICH CAUSED THE BATTERIES TO IGNITED COULD NOT BE DETERMINED. THE BATTERIES AND AFFECTED FREIGHT WERE STAGED FROM PROPER DISPOSAL THROUGH A HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL VENDOR.

PLAINS EMPLOYEE REYNALDO AMARO WAS TRAVELING WEST ON US 67 WHEN HE LOST CONTROL OF HIS TRUCK, LEFT THE ROADWAY AND ENTERED THE NORTH SHOULDER/BARROW DITCH. AS HE ATTEMPTED TO BRING THE TRACTOR/TRAILER BACK ON TO THE ROADWAY THE TRUCK AND TRAILER OVERTURNED (ROLLED OVER ONTOTHE PASSENGER SIDE) ON THE HIGHWAY SURFACE. AMARO'S TRUCK VERRED INTO THE NORTH SHOULDER AND FLIPPED OVER, SAID THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY OFFICERS THAT INVESTIGATED THE CRASH. AMARO IS AN EMPLOYEE OF PLAINS MARKETING, L.P. WORKING OUT OF THE BIG LAKE, TEXAS TRUCK DISTRICT.    AMARO WAS TAKEN TO THE MC CAMEY HOSPITAL BY MC CAMEY EMS AMBULANCE SERVICE. HE WAS EXAMINED AND EVALUATED THERE AND SUBSEQUENTLY TRANSPORTED TO MEDICAL CENTER HOSPITAL IN ODESSA, TX.    THE CARGO TANK WAS RUPTURED AND ALLOWED CRUDE OIL TO LEAK ONTO AN AREA OF US 67 AND THE TX DOT RIGHT-OG-WAY WHERE THE SEMITRAILER CAME TO REST. PLAINS' BIG LAKE EMEREGENCY RESPONSE TEAM CONTAINED THE SPILL USING CONTAINMENT BOOMS, ABSORBENTS, AND SOIL. DURATION OF THE SPILL WAS APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR. THE CARGO TANK RUPTURE WAS A VERTICAL BREACH IN THE LOWER PASSENGER SIDE QUADRANT OF THE TANK SHELL, MIDWAY BETWEEN THE FRONT AND REAR BULKHEADS; APPROXIMATELY 6" IN LENGTH AND 1" IN WIDTH.
column169: PLAINS MARKETING, L.P. INTENDS TO INCREASE DRIVER TRAINING ON SITUATIONAL AWARENESS AND INCREASED ATTENTION TO POTENTIAL HAZARDS OF DRIVING WHEN FATIGUED OR DROWSY. ADDITIONALLY, PLAINS MARKETING, L.P. WILL INCLUDE ORIENTATION AND TRAINING FOR ITS DRIVERS ON MAINTAINING PROPER VEHICLE SPEED AND CONTROL, WITH SPECIFIC EMPHASIS ON LEARNING TO SAFELY DRIVE A VEHICLE OFF THE ROAD AND BACK ONTO IT. KNOWING HOW TO HANDLE THOSE SCENARIOS CAN DRASTICALLY INCREASE THE CHANCES OF AVOIDING A SERIOUS CRASH.

column168: ON JANUARY 26, 2014 TROOPER JASON CLARK, D101R09 APPROACHED A BULK PNEUMATIC TANKER. TRUCK TRACTOR ILLEGALLY PARKED ON THE SHOULDER OF THE EAST BOUND REST AREA ON RAMP OF I 40 E/B. THE DRIVER WAS CITED FOR ILLEGAL PARKING., CITATION # 199236G. FOR PARKING ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY, MARKED NO PARKING. TROOPER CLARK CITED THE DRIVER AND NOTICED A LEAK COMING FROM UNDERNEATH THE TANKER TO THE SHOULDER. REVIEWING THE SPILLAGE, TROOPER CLARK NOTIFIED DICKSON COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AND LATER TENNESSEE DOT, TO INCLUDE THE TENNESSEE EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY TO GET ADVISE TO THE SPILLAGE. THE TANKER WAS LOADED WITH 37,000 POUNDS PLUS OF NA 3077, HAZARDOUS WASTE, CLASS 9 NA, PG III. ADDITIONAL TROOPERS ARRIVED TO EVACUATE AND CLOSE EAST BOUND REST AREA TO FOLLOW UP ON EMERGENCY SERVICES. CLEAN HARBORS, AN EMERGENCY SPILL AND REMEDIATION COMPANY WAS SENT BY THE GENERATOR OF THE WASTE. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS MOVED TO THE REAR OF THE REST AREA. THERE WAS A GASKET LEAK IN THE 4" CAP TO THE WATER DISCHARGE LINE. APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF WATER LEAKED FROM THE FROZEN GASKET THAT HAD DETERIORATED ON THE CAP HOLDING ON THE WATER LINE.
column169: THE FAILURE OF THE GASKET WAS AS A RESULT OF THE WEATHER (INCLEMENT AND COLD) AND WAS NOT A RESULT OF DRIVER ERROR OR NEGLIGENCE. DURING INCLEMENT, WINTER WEATHER, THE GASKETS AND CAPS WILL BE CHANGED ON A REGULAR BASIS TO PREVENT SAID SPILLAGE HAPPENING AGAIN IN THE FUTURE. THE WEATHER WREAKS HAVOC ON THE GASKETS AND CAPS ON THE WATER DISCHAGE LINES AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER.

It was reported that a multivehicle accident caused the tractor to roll over, releasing UN2922 to the roadway and soil ditch. Due to the roll over accident, extensive damage occurred to the plastic totes that were used to transport the corrosive liquid. A replacement tanker was brought on site to carry any recovered product away from the release location. Once the product was transferred the trailer was righted and the cleanup operations took place. Absorbents and neutralizing agents were deployed and the impacted roadway was swept up. The lanes of traffic were then allowed to flow, unimpeded.     The release lasted approximately 10 hours. Diking was used to limit the migration of the release into the soil ditch. Boom and pads were used to collect some of the released material. All cleanup debris was collected and containerized for profiling and disposal. Soils were excavated once utility locates were completed.

column168: A CAR SPUN OUT OF CONTROL, DID A 360 DEGREE OUR DRIVER MOVED TO LEFT LANE THE CAR AGAIN HIT THE BRAKES AND SPUN OUT AND MOVED TO THE LEFT LANE, OUR DRIVER COULD NOT STOP OR CHANGE LANE DO TO TRAFFIC HIT THE CAR ON THE RIGHT FRONT CAUSING HIM TO LOSE CONTROL AND OVERTURN. THE ROAD WAS CLOSED, HAZMAT & EMERGENCY PERSONNEL DISTRIBUTED ABSORBENT PADS AND BOOMS TO CONTAIN THE LEAKING GASOLINE. APPROX. 630 GALLONS LEAKED UNTIL THE TRAILER WAS OFF LOADED INTO ANOTHER TRAILER. HOLES HAD TO BE CUT INTO THE TRAILER BECAUSE IT WAS ON IT'S SIDE. THE GASOLINE WAS LEAKING FROM THE MANHOLE LIDS & OVERFILL PROBE ON TOP OF TRAILER. IT WAS LEAKING AT A SLOW PACE FROM #1&2 COMPARTMENTS. IT TOOK THE HAZMAT CLEANUP CREW ABOUT 12 HOURS. IT WAS 4 HOURS BEFORE THEY ARRIVED ON SITE DUE TO THE FREEZING RAIN.
column169: HAD SAFETY MEETING SUGGESTING, DEFENSIVE DRIVING IN WINTER WEATHER CONDITIONS, SLOWER SPEEDS, LONG FOLLOWING DISTANCE BETWEEN VEHICLES. WAYS TO IDENTIFY FREEZING RAIN.

column168: ON THE NOTATED DATE AND TIME, FTT DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO LOAD PRODUCT INTO HIS TRAILER, WHEN HE EXPERIENCED AN EQUIPMENT FAILURE WHICH RESULTED IN A LOSS/SPILL OF PRODUCT.    THE TRAILER VENT TUBE WAS CLOGGED WITH PRODUCT AND WAS NOT VENTING PROPERLY, WHICH CAUSED THE GAUGE ON THE TRAILER TO DISPLAY A FALSE READING. THE DRIVER THEN INITIONED HIS PUMP AND BEGAN LOADING PRODUCT. ONCE PRODUCT BEGAN TO TRANSFER TO THE TRAILER, THE PRESSURE INCORRECTLY BUILT UP DO TO THE VENT TUBE NOT VENTING. PRODUCT THEN FORCED ITS WAY THROUGH THE VENT TUBE AND BEGAN TO EXIT THROUGH THE TOP OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE PRODUCT TRANSFER AND BEGAN CONTAINMENT MEASURES. THE CLOGGED VENT ACCOMPANIED BY THE PRESSURE BUILD UP IN THE TRAILER CAUSED THE GAUGE TO BE PERMANENTLY DAMAGED. (THE GAUGE HAS SINCE BEEN REPAIRED AND THE TRAILER IS BACK IN SERVICE).
column169: THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED, ABSORBED, AND MORE THAN 50% OF THE PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED. THE RESIDUAL PRODUCT AND AREA AFFECTED BY THE SPILL WAS TREATED WITH OIL BAG, FERTILIZER, AND DOT APPROVED SAND. ADEQ INSPECTOR RONALD SMITH LATER NOT WITH NO AT THE SPILL SITE AND OBSERVED THE CLEAN UP MEASURES TAKEN WERE ACCEPTABLE.    TRAINING HAS SINCE BEEN PUT IN PLACE TO HAVE DRIVERS THROUGHLY INSPECT ALL VENTALATION TUBES ON THEIR EQUIPMENT TO PREVENT FURTHER EQUIPMENT FAILURES.

TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO OFFLOAD DIESEL FUEL INTO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK AT THE SC CENTRAL RAILROAD FACILITY. THE HOSE BURST, ALLOWING 50-75 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL TO ESCAPE AND SPILL ONTO THE GROUND AROUND THE TANK. SOME PRODUCT CROSSED THE DIRT ROADWAY AND WENT INTO A DITCH. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE VALVES TO STOP THE PRODUCT FROM SPILLING. A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS USED TO REMEDIATE THE AFFECTED AREA. ABSORBENT PADS WERE USED TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT IN THE DRAINAGE DITCH. THE ROADWAY WAS EXCAVATED TO REMOVE PRODUCT FROM THE ROADWAY. RECENT RAINS KEPT FREE PRODUCT ON TOP OF THE ROADWAY, ALLOWING FOR A SIMPLE ESCAVATION. ALL PRODUCT WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY, INCLUDING ABSORBENT PADS AND EXCAVATED DIRT REMOVED FROM THE ROADWAY.
column169: Driver was trained on inspection and maintenance of hoses to avoid future similar instances.

column168: The driver backed into metal bollards adjacent to gasoline dispensers while positioning tanker truck to off-load gasoline into the facilities underground storage tanks.  The valves associated with the unloading lines were damaged allowing approximately 30 gallons of gasoline to leak onto the parking lot.  Absorbent material was immediately placed on the gasoline.  A environmental contractor containerized the spent absorbent material in 55-gallon drums and properly disposed of the material as hazardous waste.  The leak was reported to the West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection and corrective action was required.
column169: Woodford Transport will provide additional training to prevent similar occurrences.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: ON JANUARY 3RD, 2014 (JEFF STIVERSON) WAS DELIVERING A LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID TO BIOVA INC. LOCATED AT 2325 NORTH LOOP ROAD AMES, IOWAW 50010.  I ARRIVED AT 10:50 AM AT WHICH TIME I WAS MET BY A WORKER, WHO OPENED THE GATE FOR ME.  THIS WORKER WENT BACK TO PLACING A SIGN ON THE TANK MARKING IT AS SULFURIC AICD, I ASKED HIM IF THEY HAD FROOM FOR MY LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID AND IF THEY HAD THE OTHER HALF OF THE FLANGE.  WE DRIVERS DO NOT CARRY FLANGES ON OUR TRUCK AND I NEEDED THIS PART TO HOOK MY 2" HOSE TO THEIR TANK HE WAS NOT SURE SO HE WENT INTO THE OFFICE AND I MET MICHAEL DEJONG, WHO WAS SIAD TO BE THE HEAD PERSON IN CHARGE.    I TOLD MICHAEL DEJONG I WAS THERE TO DELIVER A LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID AND I NEEDED A WAY TO HOOK UP TO THEIR TANK.  MICHAEL AND I WENT INTO THE SUPPLY ROOM AND FOUND A 2" COUPLER THAT WOULD WORK TO OFF LOAD FROM MY TRUCK INTO THE SULFURIC ACID TANK.  BOTH MICHAEL DEJONG AND I PLACED THE NEW FITTING ON THEIR SULFURIC ACID TANK.  AT THIS TIME I SHOWED MICHAEL THE BILL OF LADING AND THE CERTIFICATE OF ANALYSIS AND HE SIGNED MY COPY.  AFTER SIGNING MY BILL OF LADING, I ASKED MICHAEL DEJONG IF THEY HAD ENOUGH ROOM FOR THE LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID.  MR. DEJONG SAID "OUR TANK IS A 3000 GALLON TANK AND THERE IS 500 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID IN THE TANK".  I TOLD HIM THAT I HAD ABOUT 2000 GALLONS AND ASKED HIM IF IT WAS OKAY TO UNLOAD, MICHAEL DEJONG SAID "GO AHEAD".    I HOOKED UP THE 2" HOSE FROM MY SULFURIC ACID TANKER ONTO THEIR SULFURIC ACID TANK AND OPENED THEIR VALVE.  AFTER OPENING THE VALVE ON MY TANKER I WALKED OVER TO THE CONNECTION AT THE BIOVA SULFURIC ACID TANK, THATS WHEN THE TANK STARTED TO SHAKE.  A CLOUD OF GAS STARTED DOWN THE OUTSIDE OF THE BIOVA SULFURIC ACID TANK AND I RAN BACK TO MY TANK TO SHUT OFF THE VALVE.  WHILE SHUTTING OFF THE VALVE I WAS OVER TAKEN BY THE GAS.  THE VALVE WAS NOW CLOSED SO I HEADED INTO THE BIOVA OFFICE TO INFORM MR. DEJUNG THAT THERE WAS GAS COMING OUT OF THEIR SULFURIC ACID TANK AND IF HE WAS SURE THAT IT WAS SULFURIC ACID IN THE TANK.  MICHAEL DEJONG REPLIED "THERE IS HYDROCHLORIC ACID BUT THAT'S OKAY THEY ARE COMPATIBLE ACIDS."  I SAID "NO THEY ARE NOT, YOU NEED TO COME AND SEE THE CLOUD OF GAS, I NEED HELP!"  I LEFT MICHAEL DEJONG AND WENT OUTSIDE TO SHUT MY TRUCK OFF AND TO CALL MY BOSS.    I CALLED CHRIS BALTUSHIS (MY BOSS) HE ASKED IF 911 WAS CALLED AND IF NOT WE NEEDED TO CALL THEM NOW.  MICHAEL DEJONG CAME OUT OF THE BIOVA BUILDING AND TOLD ME THAT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON THE WAY.  CHRIS ASKED ME WHO AUTHORIZED ME TO UNLOAD THE LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID, I TOLD HIM THAT MICHAEL DEJONG AUTHORIZED IT AND AT THIS TIME HANDED MR. DEJONG MY PHONE.  MICHAEL DEJONG TOLD CHRIS THAT HE AUTHORIZED ME TO UNLOAD THE SULFURIC ACID INTO THEIR SULFURIC ACID TANK.    THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND MICHAEL DEJONG ASKED THEM TO GIVE ME MEDICAL TREATMENT.  THEY TRANSPORTED ME TO THE HOSPITAL.
column169: OUR DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INFORMED TO CALL THE TERMINAL MANAGER IF ANY QUESTIONS ARISE DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  THE PLANT WE DELIVERD, TO BIOVIA, NEEDS SOME WORK ON THEIR INTERNAL CONTROLS.

FIRST RESPONDERS SECURED DOME LID AND PLACED CONTAINER TO COLLECT LEAKING FUEL OIL.    USED A SECOND FUEL OIL TANK TO TRANSFER PRODUCT FROM DAMAGED TRUCK. WRECKER REMOVED DAMAGE MUCH FROM SIDE OF ROAD.
column169: UNFORTUNATE EVENT. NOT SURE WHAT STEPS NEED TO BE CHANGED TO PREVENT REOCCURENCE.  HAVE HAD ALL DRIVERS REVIEW FUNDEMENTAL INSURANCE ROLL OVER TRAINING VIDEO. SAFETY MEETINGS TO REINFORCE IMPORTANCE OF BASIC PRETRIP INSPECTIONS, MAINTENANCE AWARENESS OF ROAD CONDITIONS AND SURROUNDINGS.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING AT THE MARATHON STATION THE TANK OVERFILLED AND DID NOT STOP, CAUSING IT TO BACK UP THRU THE VAPOR RECOVERY. THE VAPOR FITTING MUST NOT OF BEEN ON THE TUBE TIGHT DUE TO SNOW & ICE IN THE WELL AND WHEN IT OVER FLOWED FUEL CAME OUT OF THE VAPOR WELL. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE FLOW. APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLON WAS SPILLED OUT ONTO THE LOT RUNNING DOWNHILL INTO THE DRAINAGE DITCH. THE DRIVER CALLED THE FIRE DEPT. IMMEDIATELY AND THEN CALLED KAREN WHO CALLED THE CLEAN-UP CREW THAT THE COMING USES. THE DRIVER MADE AN ERROR BY LOOKING AT THE WRONG NUMBER CHECKING HIS STICK READING WITH HIS TANK CHART. THE DRIVER FEELS IF THE CUSTOMER HAD HIS WELLS FREE OF ICE & SHOW THE FITTING.
column169: HAVE DRIVERS DOUBLE CHECK STICK READING AND TANK CHARTS. HAVE CUSTOMERS CHECK WELLS KEEP THEM FREE OF ICE & SNOW AND MAKE SURE THEY ARE NOT BROKE.

column168: DELIVERY OF HEATING OIL TO WRONG RESIDENTIAL ADDRESS. DRIVER STARTED PUMPING AND HEARD NO VENT ALARM SO HE SHUT OFF AFTER 18 GALLONS. HE KNOCKED ON DOOR AND WENT IN BASEMENT TO DISCOVER THEY HAD GAS HEAT AND THE TANK WAS REMOVED. (THE FILL AND VENT PIPING WERE STILL IN PLACE BUT WERE NOT CONNECTED TO ANYTHING. DRIVER USED CLAY ABSORBENT AND PADS TO CONTAIN SPILL UNTIL OUR SERVICE TECHS ARRIVED TO CLEANUP.  FIRE COMPANY WAS CALLED BY THEY JUST EXAMINED THE SPILL AND LEFT SINCE WE HAD IT CONTAINED AND A CLEANUP CREW WAS IN ROUTE.
column169: ON NEW CUSTOMER'S WE ALWAYS CHECK THE TANK PRIOR TO A DELIVERY. SINCE THIS WAS TO BE MADE A REPEAT CUSTOMER THE DRIVER WAS TO JUST DROP THE OIL. PROBLEM WAS HE WENT TO WRONG HOUSE. ONLY SUGGESTIONS I CAN MAKE IS THERE SHOULD BE AN ORDINANCE THAT STATES THAT THE FILL & VENT PIPING BE REMOVED WHEN THE TANK IS TAKEN OUT WHCIH WOULD MAKE THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT TOTALLY IMPOSSIBLE.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Procedures
column168: ON JANUARY 13, 2014 A PACKAGE CONTAINING DANGEROUS GOODS (DG) WAS SHIPPED VIA UPS GROUND WITHOUT THE REQUIRED LABELING, PER 49 CFR 173.421(A) & 173.422(A).  ON APRIL 28, 2014 REUTER-STOKES, INC. WAS CONTACTED BY THE CUSTOMER WHO RECEIVED THE UNDECLARED PACKAGE IN JANUARY. THE CUSTOMER REQUESTED COPIES OF MISSING DOCUMENTS RELATED TO THE PACKAGE (NON-DOT DOCUMENTS). UPON INITIAL REVIEW IT WAS CONFIRMED THAT THE NON-DOT DOCUMENTS WERE MISSING AND WERE SUBSEQUENTLY SEND TO THE CUSTOMER.  THIS ISSUE PROMPTED AN INTERNAL INVESTIGATION. THE INVESTIGATION INDICATED THAT ALTHOUGH ALL NECESSARY TRAINING, DOT/IATA, HAD BEEN COMPLETED BY APPLICABLE PERSONNEL, THE PROCESS USED TO IDENTIFY THE PACKAGE AS DG FAILED, CAUSING THIS PACKAGE TO BE SHIPPED UNDECLARED.
column169: IN RESPONSE TO THIS ISSUE REUTER-STOKES, INC. IS SELF-REPORTING THE UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT TO THE U.S. DOT, PHMSA OFFICE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  IN ADDITION, REUTER-STOKES, INC. HAS UTILIZED HUMAN PERFORMANCE LEARNING PRINCIPLES TO IDENTIFY THE FOLLOWING APPROACHES TO IMPROVE THE DEFENSE IN THE MATERIAL HANDLING OPERATION AND PROCESSES:  -SHORT TERM (IMMEDIATE ACTION): RE-TRAIN ALL APPLICABLE PERSONNEL ON HOW TO IDENTIFY SPECIFIC PRODUCTS AS DG (WEAK DEFENSE)  -MEDIUM-TERM: IMPLEMENT VISUAL &/ OR PHYSICAL IDENTIFIERS SUCH AS LABELS AND SEGREGATED STORAGE CAGES FOR THE DG ITEMS (STRONGER DEFENSE)  -LONG TERM: UPDATE APPLICABLE PRODUCTION DRAWINGS TO INCLUDE DG LABELING (STRONGER DEFENSE)  -LONG TERM: UPDATE DIGITAL SYSTEMS USED TO ENSURE DG ITEMS ARE FLAGGED PRIOR TO SHIPPING (STRONGEST DEFENSE)

column168: VEHICLE #1 - MODOT SNOWPLOW    VEHICLE #2 - HEIL OIL CO. TRANSPORT/TRAILER    VEHICLE #1 WAS IN LANE ONE WHILE VEHICLE #2 WAS IN LANE FOUR ON SOUTHBOUND INTERSTATE 55 NORTH BAYLESS AVENUE. THE CRASH OCCURRED AS A VEHICLE #1 MADE A UNSAFE LANE CHANGE FROM LANE ONE ACROSS ALL LANES AND CUTTING ACROSS THE GORE-POINT ONTO THE SOUTHBOUND INTERSTATE 55 RAMP TO BAYLESS AVENUE. DRIVER #2 ATTEMPTED TO AVOID THE COLLISION WITH VEHICLE #1 BY STEERING TO THE RIGHT. WHEN DRIVER #2 STEERED TO THE RIGHT, HIS TRAILER BEGAN TO SLIDE ON THE SNOW COVERED ROADWAY.  DRIVER #2 APPLIED THE BRAKES IN AN ATTEMPT TO REGAIN CONTROL OF THE TRAILER BUT WAS UNABLE TO AS THE TRAILER BEGAN TO JACKKNIFE. THE FRONT LEFT OF THE TRAILER PULLED BY DRIVER #2 STRUCK THE RIGHT REAR OF VEHICLE #1 RESULTING IN PUNCTURES IN DRIVER #2'S TRAILER. BOTH VEHICLES CAME TO REST ON THE SOUTHBOUND INTERSTATE 55 RAMP TO BAYLESS AVENUE FACING SOUTH. APPROXIMATELY 2200 GALLONS OF GASOLINE SPILLED ONTO INTERSTATE 55. THE FUEL RAN DOWN A STEEP SLOPE OFF THE SHOULDER OF INTERSTATE 55 AND FLOWED NORTH INTO A DRAINAGE DITCH. THE FUEL MIGRATED UNDERNEATH INTERSTATE 55 VIA A STORM CULVERT AND POOLED UP.

column168: CHEVRON STATION MANAGER CALLED THE CHEVRON EMERGENCY INFORMATION CENTER HOTLINE TO REPORT A GASOILINE SPILL OF 10-15 GALLONS AT THE EWA BEACH, HI STATION. THE STATION MANAGER STATED THAT THE SPILL OCCURED WHEN A FUEL TRUCK'S HOSE CAME LOOSE DURING  A DELIVERY. NO GASOLINE WENT INTO ANY DRAINS OR WATERWAYS AND THERE WERE NO HUMAN EXPOSURES OR INJURIES. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE DELIVERY DRIVERM AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ALSO RESPONDED ON SCENE. THE STATION MANAGER ALSO NOTIFED HIS SUPERVISOR VIA EMAIL.    THE CHEVRON EMERGENCY INFORMATION CENTER NOTIFIED THE ON DUTY PERSON ABOUT THE INCIDENT. THE ON DUTY PERSON THEN NOTIFIED CHEVRON HES AND THE STATION MANAGER'S SUPERVISOR TO VERIFY THAT THEY KNEW ABOUT THE INCIDENT.    CHEVRON HES NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER VIA PHONE CALL THAT THE CAM-LOCKS ON THE HOSE CAME LOOSE WHICH CAUSED THE UNDERGROUND TANK TO OVERFILL.
column169: REVIEW AND UNDERSTAND THE PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES WITH EMPHASIS ON THE REASONS FOR THOSE PROCEDURES, COUPLED WITH SPECIAL ATTENTION TO THE 'READ-AND-RECOGNITION' IMPORTANCE DURING THE PERFORMANCE OF THOSE PROCEDURES. UNDERSTANDING THE REQUIRMENT TO 'STOP-AND-EVALUATE' UPON NOTICING ANY DISCREPANCIES WHILE PERFORMING THE PROPER PROCEDURES.    COMMUNICATION WITH ALL DRIVERS ABOUT THIS INCIDENT HAS HAPPEND AND THE IMPORTANCE OF GETTING ENOUGH SLEEP AND SLOWING DOWN HAS BEEN TALKED ABOUT. ALSO THE IMPORTANCE OF LISTENING TO ALL DIRECTIONS AND IF THEY ARE UNSURE OF ANYTHING THEY ARE TO CALL THEIR SUPERVISOR BEFORE OPENING ANY VALCES. THIS DRIVER WILL BE GOING BACK INTO TRAINING FOR A DAY, AND WILL BE SENT BACK TO WORK WHEN SUPERVISOR DEEMS HE IS READY TO HANDLE THE DETAILS ASSOCIATED WITH THIS JOB.

column168: While filling his truck, driver did not shut load line valve, got out of sequence when pump shut down on low level.  Driver set barrel count at 180 bbls, pump shut down on 171 bbls leaving 9 bbls on counter.  After driver cleared memory due to autoshutoff, he did not know pump could re-start when tank levels reached 5 ft. If bbls were left on mechanical meter head it would pump that count. Driver did not know to push stop button on counter if all bbls did not pump off.   Approximately 9 bbls spilled within containment.  Product was cleaned up by third party contractor.
column169: Communicate to all drivers potential for pump re-start.  If drivers get out of routine, start back at the beginning.  Educate the understanding of the emergency shutoff.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Driver was loading crude from tank battery into trailer.  Driver had issue with hydrogen sulfide odor and moved from the immediate area. He was relying on the automatic audible alarm to warm of pending full truck.  Audible alarm was not triggered, trailer filled, and product overfilled from the vent on top.  Before the driver was able to shutdown the pump, approximately 18 barrels of crude was lost to the vent line.  Product was along the lease property and cleaned by third party.
column169: Safety Flash went out to all facilities to remind drivers that they must remain with the pump.  Should they need to leave the immediate area due to odors, pumps are to be shut off and not allowed to run.  Automatic shutoff systems were retested throughout the fleet.  No other deficiencies were noted.
